 demonstrate the intertwining of sexual, economic, and familial motivations for migration. Further, Carrillo shows that sexual globalization must be regarded as a bidirectional, albeit uneven, process of exchange between countries in the global north and the global south. With this approach, Carrillo challenges the view that gay men from countries like Mexico would logically want to migrate to a “more sexually enlightened” country like the United States—a partial and limited understanding, given the dynamic character of sexuality in countries such as Mexico, which are becoming more accepting of sexual diversity. Pathways of Desire also provides a helpful analytical framework for the simultaneous consideration of structural and cultural factors in social scientific studies of sexuality. Carrillo explains the patterns of cross-cultural interaction that sexual migration generates and—at the most practical level—shows how the intricacies of cross-cultural sexual and romantic relations may affect the sexual health and HIV risk of transnational immigrant populations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGay communityzUnited States. 0aGay community-United States. 0aGay menzMexicovCase studies. 0aGay men-Mexico-Case studies. 0aHispanic American gay menvCase studies. 0aHispanic American gay men-Case studies. 0aMexicansxRelocationzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aMexicans-Relocation-United States-Case studies. 0aMexico-Emigration and immigration-Social aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aHIV risk.  aMexican gay men.  aSan Diego.  across-cultural interaction.  asexual freedom.  asexual globalization.  asexual health.  asexual migration.  atransnational immigrant populations.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831